<AnchorPane prefHeight="500.0" prefWidth="800.0" xmlns="http://javafx.com/javafx" xmlns:fx="http://javafx.com/fxml" fx:controller="model.resources.InstructionsMenuController">
   <children>
      <VBox prefHeight="500.0" prefWidth="800.0">
         <children>
            <GridPane prefHeight="110.0" prefWidth="800.0">
              <columnConstraints>
                <ColumnConstraints hgrow="SOMETIMES" minWidth="10.0" prefWidth="100.0" />
                <ColumnConstraints hgrow="SOMETIMES" minWidth="10.0" prefWidth="100.0" />
                  <ColumnConstraints hgrow="SOMETIMES" minWidth="10.0" prefWidth="100.0" />
              </columnConstraints>
              <rowConstraints>
                <RowConstraints minHeight="10.0" prefHeight="30.0" vgrow="SOMETIMES" />
              </rowConstraints>
               <children>
                   <Button fx:id="backButton" mnemonicParsing="false" onMouseClicked="#backButtonClicked" text="←" translateX="15.0" translateY="15.0" GridPane.halignment="LEFT" GridPane.valignment="TOP" />
                  <Label text="Instructions" translateX="10.0" translateY="10.0" GridPane.columnIndex="1">
                     <font>
                        <Font name="Ubuntu Bold" size="43.0" />
                     </font>
                  </Label>
               </children>
            </GridPane>
            <HBox prefHeight="395.0" prefWidth="800.0">
               <children>
                   <TextArea fx:id="textArea" editable="false" prefHeight="305.0" prefWidth="700.0" text="Welcome to Name Sayer!&#10;&#10;Name Sayer is a name pronounciation application designed and created by Rowan Hart and Michelle Tan. It has been designed to improve users' pronounciation of difficult names, an important skill in an increasingly multicultural world.&#10;This Instructions page is simply to get you started, for more detailed help please refer to the User Manual packaged with Name Sayer.&#10;&#10;Practise:&#10;&#10;-Enter Names: From here you can enter the names you wish to practise. You can type the names by hand or upload them from a text file.  You also have the option to save the list of names to a text file for later use. Name Sayer will auotmatically detect any names not in the current working database and highlight them red.&#10;&#10;-Practise names: From here you can listen to the names you have created, either in a list or individually. Right click either play button te hear only the first names. You can also rate the recordings using the ★ button. Right click this button to view all previously rated recordings.&#10;&#10;-Record: Here you can choose a particular name to practise in further detail. You can record yourself pronouncing it, then compare that with the database name numerous times. If there are multiple recordings for that name, you can choose which one to play by pressing the ☰ button.&#10;&#10;Listen:&#10;&#10;-From here you can listen to the names in the currently loaded database without having to enter any names to practise. You can also rate them to mark loq quality recordings for later deletion.&#10;&#10;Settings:&#10;&#10;From here you can edit the settings of the program to maximize your user experience. You can:&#10;-View these instructions.&#10;-Choose a custom theme.&#10;-Check Name Sayer is currently reading your microphone volume.&#10;-Test your speaker volume and adjust system volume accordingly.&#10;-Load a new database of names to practise. Please note the selected folder must only contain wave (.wav extension) files or folders.&#10;&#10;For further information or help regarding Name Sayer, please email rhar768@aucklanduni.ac.nz or mtan264@aucklanduni.ac.nz." wrapText="true">
                     <HBox.margin>
                        <Insets bottom="50.0" left="50.0" right="50.0" top="50.0" />
                     </HBox.margin>
                     <cursor>
                        <Cursor fx:constant="NONE" />
                     </cursor>
                  </TextArea>
               </children>
            </HBox>
         </children>
      </VBox>
   </children>
</AnchorPane>
